	<text id="material" x="37" y="65" width="697" height="346" autosize="" style="WIZARD_TEXT" visible="true" fx="SHOW" hidefx="HIDE" scroll="AUTO">
		<content translate="true">&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Discussion Topic&lt;/B&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;As toddlers explore their world, they are learning how to regulate their emotions. Watch this video to better understand tantrums and how adults teach emotional regulation through their example.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Video / Discussion&lt;/B&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;Watch “Tantrums Happen” from the Talaris &lt;I&gt;Everyday Moments Count&lt;/I&gt; DVD. Following the video, ask the parents to think of some common reasons why young children have tantrums? &lt;/P&gt;&lt;TEXTFORMAT BLOCKINDENT="16"&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/TEXTFORMAT&gt;&lt;TEXTFORMAT BLOCKINDENT="16"&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;Possible Responses:&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/TEXTFORMAT&gt;&lt;LI&gt;Physical or emotional discomfort&lt;/LI&gt;&lt;LI&gt;Insufficient language skills to express needs&lt;/LI&gt;&lt;LI&gt;Attempt to assert independence&lt;/LI&gt;&lt;LI&gt;Wanting attention&lt;/LI&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Feedback&lt;/B&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;As children mature, they develop the capacity to regulate their emotions. In order to develop this ability, children need:&lt;/P&gt;&lt;LI&gt;Time to develop &lt;/LI&gt;&lt;LI&gt;Support from caregivers to identify their feelings&lt;/LI&gt;&lt;LI&gt;Skills to manage emotions in situations where they are likely to lose control&lt;/LI&gt;</content>
	</text>
